        "min": 0,
        "max": 100,
        "description": "The tax percentage to apply. Only active when 'Currency + VAT' mode is selected. It calculates the tax and adds it to the principal before conversion."
      }
    ],
    "outputs_json": [
      {
        "name": "textResult",
        "label": "Converted Text",
        "unit": null,
        "rounding": null,
        "description": "The final written representation of the number, formatted according to the selected mode, currency, and grammatical case."
      },
      {
        "name": "calculatedTotal",
        "label": "Numeric Total (VAT Mode)",
        "unit": null,
        "rounding": "2",
        "description": "If VAT mode is active, this displays the numeric total (Principal + Tax) before it is converted to text."
      }
    ],
    "examples_json": [
      {
        "input": {
          "inputNumber": "1250.50",
          "conversionMode": "Check Writing",
          "currency": "USD"
        },
        "output": {
          "textResult": "One thousand two hundred fifty and 50/100 dollars"
        }
      }
    ],
    "formula_md": "While linguistic conversion relies on dictionary mapping rather than a mathematical formula, the **VAT (Value Added Tax)** calculation uses standard percentage logic. \n\nWhen calculating the **Total Amount** including tax:\n\n$$ Total = Principal \\times \\left( 1 + \\frac{VAT\\_Rate}{100} \\right) $$\n\nWhere:\n* **Principal** is the input number.\n* **VAT_Rate** is the percentage tax.\n\nFor **Check Writing**, the fractional part is derived as:\n\n$$ Fraction = \\text{round}((Number - \\text{floor}(Number)) \\times 100) $$\n\nThe result is then formatted as \"XX/100\".",
    "assumptions_md": "* **Scale:** The converter uses the short scale system (standard in US and modern UK English) where a billion is $10^9$, not $10^{12}$.\n* **Rounding:** Monetary values are rounded to two decimal places (nearest cent/penny) before conversion.\n* **Language:** The output is strictly in English, regardless of the currency selected (e.g., 'RUB' outputs 'rubles', not 'рублей').\n* **Limit:** The maximum number of digits supported is 300.",
    "howto_json": [
      {
        "question": "How do I use this tool to write a bank cheque?",
        "answer": "<p>Writing a cheque requires a specific format to be legally valid and secure. Follow these steps:</p><ol><li>Enter the exact amount (e.g., <b>1234.56</b>) in the input field.</li><li>Select <b>'Check Writing'</b> from the Mode options.</li><li>Ensure the currency is set to <b>USD</b> (or your relevant currency).</li><li>Click <b>Calculate</b>.</li></ol><p>The result will appear as <i>'One thousand two hundred thirty-four and 56/100 dollars'</i>. Transcribe this text onto the legal line of your cheque. The '56/100' format is standard banking practice to clearly denote cents.</p>"
      },
      {
        "question": "What is the difference between Title Case and Sentence Case?",
        "answer": "<p>These options control the capitalization of the output text, which changes based on where you intend to use the text:</p><ul><li><b>Sentence case:</b> Capitalizes only the first letter of the first word (e.g., <i>'Five hundred dollars'</i>). This is best for use inside a standard paragraph or sentence.</li><li><b>Title Case:</b> Capitalizes the first letter of every major word (e.g., <i>'Five Hundred Dollars'</i>). This is ideal for headings, titles, or formal standalone declarations on certificates.</li></ul>"
      },
      {
        "question": "How does the VAT calculation feature work?",
        "answer": "<p>The VAT (Value Added Tax) mode helps you determine the final invoice amount including tax without needing a separate calculator. Select <b>'Currency + VAT'</b> mode, enter your net amount (pre-tax price), and specify the tax percentage in the <b>VAT Rate</b> field. The tool will mathematically add the tax to your number ($Total = Net + Tax$) and then convert that final total into words automatically.</p>"
      }
    ]
